{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> χάρις</b> [ᾰ], ἡ, <br /> <i>genitive</i> χάρῐτος: <i>accusative</i> χάριν [ῑ in arsi, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 5.874]\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], etc.; also χάριτα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 6.41, 9.107, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Electra” 61, “Hel.” 1378, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Historia Graeca (Hellenica)” 3.5.16, 3rd c.BC: Phylarchus Historicus 24 1st c.AD: Josephus Historicus, “PGen.” 47.17 (4th c.AD), etc. (un-Attic, _accusative_ to Moer.p.414P.): χάριταν “Corpus Glossariorum Latinorum”: _plural_ χάριτες\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <i>dative</i> χάρισι, χαρίτεσσι, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 6.237, 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 17.51, 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 7.93 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: (χαίρω):—<b>grace</b>: <br /><Level2><b>__I</b></Level2> in objective sense, <b>outward grace</b> or <b>fauour, beauty,</b> properly of persons or their portraits, θεσπεσίην δ᾽ ἄρα τῷ γε χάριν κατεχεύατ᾽ Ἀθήνη [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 2.12, etc.; χάριν ἀμφιχέαι κεφαλῇ 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 65; εὐμόρφων δὲ κολοσσῶν ἔχθεται χ. ἀνδρί 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 417 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: <i>plural</i>, <b>graces,</b> κάλλεϊ καὶ χάρισι στίλβων [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 6.237; ὄσσοις χάριτας Ἀφροδίτης ἔχων 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Bacchae” 236; μετὰ χαρίτων \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<b>gracefully,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 2.41: less frequently of things, χ. δ᾽ ἀπελάμπετο πολλή,\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] of ear-rings, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 14.183 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; of works, ἔργοισι χάριν καὶ κῦδος ὀπάζει [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 15.320 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; of words, οὔ οἱ χ. ἀμφιπεριστέφεται ἐπέεσσιν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8.175 \">Refs</a>]; πλείστη δὲ χ. κατὰ μέτρον ἰούσης [γλώσσης] [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 720; ταὶ Διωνύσου σὺν βοηλάτα χάριτες διθυράμβῳ 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 13.19; ἡ τῶν λόγων χ. 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 4.38, compare 1st c.BC: Dionysius Halicarnassensis “de Compositione Verborum” 23; μῦθοι πληθόμενοι χαρίτων “Anthologia Graeca” 9.186 (1st c.BC: Antipater Thessalonicensis Epigrammaticus). \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__I.2</b></Level3> <b>glory,</b> Φερενίκου χ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 1.18, compare 8.57, 80. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> in subjective sense, <b>grace</b> or <b>favour felt,</b> whether on the part of the doer or the receiver (both senses appear in such phrases as ὅτ᾽.. ἡ χάρις χάριν φέροι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 779; χάρις χάριν γάρ ἐστιν ἡ τίκτουσ᾽ ἀεί [prev. author] “Aj.” 522, compare 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Helena” 1234, 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Rhetorica” 1385a16): \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.1</b></Level3> on the part of the doer, <b>grace, kindness, goodwill,</b> τινος <b>for</b> or <b>towards</b> one, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 190; τῶν Μεσσηνίων χάριτι πεισθείς 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 3.95 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; οὐ χάριτι τῇ ἐμῇ not for any <b>kind feeling towards</b> me, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 5.41: _absolutely_, εἰ δέ τις μείζων χ. 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Supplices” 960; τῆς παλαιᾶς χ. ἐκβεβλημένη 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 808 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἦ μεγάλα χ. δώρῳ σύν ὀλίγῳ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 28.24; χ. εὑρεῖν ἐναντίον τοῦ θεοῦ LXX.Gen.6.8, +others; χάριν ἔχειν πρὸς τὸν δῆμον 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Demosthenes” 7 \">LXX+3rd c.BC+</a>]; <b>partiality, favour,</b> μήτε ἔλεον μήτε συγγνώμην μήτε χ. μηδεμίαν περὶ πλείονος ποιήσασθαι τῶν νόμων [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 14.40; οὐ συμφωνοῦσιν ὀργαὶ καὶ χάριτες μακαριότητι 4th-3rd c.BC: Epicurus Philosophus “Ep.” i p.28 U., compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 740c. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> more frequently on the part of the receiver, <b>sense of favour</b> received, <b>thankfulness, gratitude,</b> χάριν καὶ κῦδος ἄροιο [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 4.95; ἀρέομαι πὰρ Σαλαμῖνος Ἀθαναίων χ. 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 1.76 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; τινος <b>for</b> a thing, οὐδέ τίς ἐστι χάρις μετόπισθ᾽ εὐεργέων [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 4.695, compare 22.319; ἀντὶ πόνων χ. 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 4.86: less frequently with \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<i>infinitive</i>, οὐκ ἄρα τις χάρις ἦεν μάρνασθαι one has, it seems, no <b>thanks for</b> fighting, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 9.316, 17.147; οἵ οἱ ἀπεμνήσαντο χ. εὐεργεσιάων 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Theogonia” 503, compare 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 1.137; χάριν φέρειν τινί 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 10(11).17; χ. τροφεῦσιν ἀμείβων 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 728 (Lyric poetry); φιλότητος ἀμειβόμεναι χ. 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Electra” 134 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; χάριν εἰδέναι τινί to acknowledge <b>a sense of favour, feel grateful,</b> once in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus, ἐγὼ δέ κέ τοι ἰδέω χ. ἤματα πάντα 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 14.235; frequently in Prose, 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 3.21, 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 2.23, 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 4.175, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; τούτων <b>for</b> a thing, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 1.6.11, etc.; τοῖς διαπεπραγμένοις 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Alexander” 62; μοι χ. οἶδεν ἐπὶ τούτοις 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Bis Acc.” 17; χ. προσειδέναι 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Apologia” 20a; ἀποδιδόναι [prev. author] “R.” 338a; τινὰ ἀποστερῆσαι χάριτος [prev. author] “Hp.Mi.” 372c; later χ. γνῶναι 2nd-3rd c.AD: Philostratus Sophista “Vita Apollonii” 2.17; πολλὴν γνοῦσα χ. 2nd c.AD(?): Xenophon Ephesius Scriptor Eroticus 3.5; χ. ἐπίσταμαι πᾶσι 2nd c.AD(?): Charito Scriptor Eroticus 3.4, compare 8.5, 2nd c.AD(?): Pollianus Epigrammaticus 5.142, 4th c.AD: Julianus Imperator “Orationes” 8.246c; also τῶν παροιχομένων ἔχειν σφι μεγάλην χ. 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 7.120, compare 1.71, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Heraclidae” 767 (Lyric poetry), “IT” 847 (Lyric poetry), 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 16.1, 4th c.BC: Hyperides Orator “adv. Athenogenem” 5 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: with <i>participle</i>, χ. ἔχειν σωθέντες [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 2.5.14 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; also χάριτας ἔχων πατρός owing him a debt of <b>gratitude,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Orestes” 244: but ἀσπασμάτων χάριν τίν᾽ ἕξει\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; what <b>thanks</b> will she have <b>for</b>.. ? [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Hec.” 830; χ. ἂν ἐν τούτῳ μείζω ἔτι ἔσχεν 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 8.87 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; χ. ὀφείλειν to owe <b>gratitude,</b> be beholden, τοῖς θεοῖς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 331, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 3.2.30; προσοφείλειν 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 3.31; χ. οὐδεμία ἐφαίνετο πρὸς Ἀθηναίων 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 5.90 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; χάριν ἀθάνατον καταθέσθαι to lay up a store of undying <b>gratitude,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] 7.178, compare 6.41; τῇ πόλει χ. καταθέσθαι 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 5.61, compare 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 1.33 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; χάριν λαβεῖν τινος receive <b>thanks from</b> one, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 1004, etc.; ἀπολαβεῖν παρά τινων 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 20.31 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τινος <b>for</b> a thing, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 2.2.5, 4th c.BC: Aeschines Orator 2.4; διπλῆν ἐξ ἐμοῦ κτήσει χάριν 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 1370; κἀπ᾽ ἐμοῦ κτήσει χ. [prev. author] “Tr.” 471; κομίσασθαι χ. 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 3.58; χάριτος τυχεῖν 4th c.BC: Lycurgus Orator 135; ἀπέχειν χάριτας 3rd c.BC: Callimachus Epicus “Epigrammata” 51.4, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τοῖς θεοῖς χάρις (i.e. ἐστί) ὅτι.., <b>thank</b> the gods that.., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 3.3.14, “Cyr.” 7.5.72; χ. τινί τινος 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Tim.” 36; τινὶ ὑπέρ τινος 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.1122a. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.3</b></Level3> <b>favour, influence,</b> opposed to force, χάριτι τὸ πλέον ἢ φόβῳ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 1.9 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; χ. καὶ δεήσει, opposed to ἀπειλῇ, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Sulla” 38. \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.4</b></Level3> <b>love-charm, philtre,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Alex.” 5, “Merc.Cond.” 40. \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> in concrete sense, <b>a favour</b> done or returned, <b>boon,</b> χάριν φέρειν τινί confer <b>a favour</b> on one, do a thing <b>to oblige</b> him, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 5.211, 874, 9.613, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 5.307, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Iphigenia Taurica” 14, “Or.” 239, 5th-6th c.BC: Andocides Orator 2.24 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] (so in <i>middle</i>, of the recipient,[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 9); ἄλλοις χ. φέροντες 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 3.54 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; χάριν θέσθαι or τίθεσθαί τινι, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 9.60, 107, 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 782, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hecuba” 1211, etc.; προσθέσθαι 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 767; χ. ὑπουργῆσαί τινι 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 635; παρασχεῖν 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 1183; πράσσειν 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Ion” 36, 896 (Lyric poetry); δράσας 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 2.40 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἀνύσαι probably in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 995 (_anapaest meter_); νέμειν [prev. author] “Aj.” 1371; χ. δοῦναί τινι 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 821, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 1489 (but χ. δοῦναι, ={χαρίζεσθαι} (1.2)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>], <b>indulge, humour,</b> ὀργῇ[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 855; γαστρί 5th c.BC: Cratinus Comicus 317); χ. χαρίζεσθαι, see at {χαρίζομαι} I.1: χ. ἀνθυπουργεῖν\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] return <b>a favour,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Fragmenta” 339; τίνειν 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 985, “Ag.” 821; χάριτας πατρῴας ἐκτίνων 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Orestes” 453, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Menexenus” 242c, etc.; χ. ἀποδιδόναι τινί 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 12.60, 28.17; ἀντί τινος 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Agesilaus” 2.29; ὑπέρ τινος 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 4.56; τῶν ἔργων τὰς χάριτας ἀποδ. τινί 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 31.24; χάριτας ἀντιδιδόναι 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 3.63 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; opposed to χάριν ἀπαιτεῖν to ask the repayment of <b>a boon,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hecuba” 276, compare 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 18.23, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 20.156; χάριτας ἀπ. 4th c.BC: Lycurgus Orator 139; χάριν ἐξαιτεῖσθαι 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 586 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; χ. ἀποστερεῖν withhold <b>a return</b> for what one has received, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Gorgias” 520c \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τὰς αὑτοῦ εἰς τοὺς φίλους χ. the <b>favours</b> one has done them, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Lg.” 729d \">Refs</a>]; χ. ἄχαρις α thankless <b>favour,</b> one which receives, or deserves, no thanks, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 545 (Lyric poetry); χ. ἀχάριτος [prev. author] “Ch.” 42 (Lyric poetry), 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Phoenissae” 1757 (Lyric poetry). \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__III.b</b></Level4> <b>grant</b> made in legal form, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “POxy.” 273.14 (1st c.AD), “PGrenf.” 2.70.5 (3rd c.AD), etc.\">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]; αἱ τῶν Σεβαστῶν χ. imperial <b>grants</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “OGI” 669.44 (Egypt, 1st c.AD). \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__III.2</b></Level3> especially in erotic sense, of <b>favours granted</b> (see. χαρίζομαι 1.3), ἀλόχου χάριν ἰδεῖν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 11.243, compare 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 1206: more frequently in _plural_, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Hiero” 1.34, 7.6, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; βίᾳ δ᾽ ἔπραξας χάριτας ἢ πείσας κόρη; [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Tragica Adespota” 402; in full, χάριτες ἀφροδισίων ἐρώτων 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “Fragmenta.” 128, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedrus” 254a, +others \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__IV</b></Level2> <b>gratification, delight,</b> τινος <b>in</b> or <b>from</b> a thing, συμποσίου [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 7.5; νίκας [prev. author] “O.” 10(11).78; ὕπνου χ. 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Orestes” 159 (Lyric poetry); even χ. γόων [prev. author] “Supp.” 79 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; also concrete, of things, <b>a delight,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “I.” 2.19 (_plural_); τὰν βοτρυώδη Διονύσου χ. οἴνας 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Bacchae” 535 (Lyric poetry), compare 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Nubes” 311 (Lyric poetry), 4th c.AD: Julianus Imperator “Orationes” 3.125b; ἔνοπτρα, παρθένων χάριτας 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Troades” 1108 (Lyric poetry): _absolutely_, Ἔρως.. εἰσάγων γλυκεῖαν χ. [prev. author] “Hipp.” 527 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; opposed to λύπη, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Electra” 821, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Helena” 655 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; opposed to πόνος, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 232 (Lyric poetry); θανεῖν πολλὴ χάρις 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 550, compare 1304; βίου χ. μεθεῖσα 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Medea” 227; οὐδεμίαν ἔχω τῷ βίῳ χάριν 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Lysistrata” 865; τοῖς δὲ σιτίοις χ. οὐδεμίαν οἶδ᾽ ἐσθίων [prev. work] 869 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; less frequently in Prose, χ. καὶ ἡδονή [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Gorgias” 462c, compare 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 20.26; τοσαύτην ἔχει χ. 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 9.10. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__V</b></Level2> δαιμόνων χάρις <b>homage due</b> to them, their <b>worship, majesty,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 182 (Lyric poetry); ἀθίκτων χ. [prev. work] 371 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; ὅρκων [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Medea” 439 (Lyric poetry). \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__V.2</b></Level3> <b>thank-offering,</b> εὐκταία χ. τινός, opposed to a common gift, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 1387, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Hiero” 8.4; ἔπεμψε χαίτην κουρίμην χ. πατρός 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Choephori” 180, compare 517; τιμὴ καὶ γέρα καὶ χ. 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Euthyphro” 15a, compare “La.” 187a. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__VI</b></Level2> Special usages: <br /><Level3><b>__VI.1</b></Level3> <i>accusative</i> <i>singular</i> as <i>adverb</i>, χ. τινός <b>in</b> any one's <b>favour, for</b> his <b>pleasure, for</b> his <b>sake,</b> χ. Ἕκτορος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 15.744 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ψεύδεσθαι γλώσσης χ. <b>for</b> one's tongue's <b>pleasure,</b> i.e. <b>for</b> talking's <b>sake,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 709, compare 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Choephori” 266 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; rarely with <i>Article</i>, τὴν Ἀθηναίων χάριν ἐστρατεύοντο [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 5.99. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__VI.1.b</b></Level4> as <i>preposition</i>, sometimes before its case (once in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus, “P.” 2.70; χάριν πλησμονῆς 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedrus” 241c; χ. φιλίας 4th-3rd c.BC: Epicurus Philosophus “Gnomologium Vaticanum - Kleine Schriften” 28 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; χ. τίνο; [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" LXX.2Ch.7.21, compare “POxy.” 743.29 (1st c.BC), etc.)\">LXX+1st c.BC+</a>], but mostly after, <b>for the sake of, on behalf of, on account of,</b> κακά νιν ἕλοιτο μοῖρα δυσπότμου χάριν χλιδᾶς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 888 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τοῦ χάρι; <b>for</b> what <b>reason?</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Plutus” 53; συγχωρῶ τοῦ λόγου χ. 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 475a \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; so ἐμὴν χάριν, χάριν σήν, <b>for</b> my, thy <b>pleasure</b> or <b>sake,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Persae” 1046 (Lyric poetry), 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hercules Furens” 1238, etc.; κείνου τε καὶ σὴν ἐξ ἴσου κοινὴν χ. 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 485 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: less frequently with the <i>Article</i>, τὴν σὴν δ᾽ ἥκω χ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Ph.” 1413 (_anapaest meter_); σοῦ τε τήν τ᾽ ἐμὴν χ. 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Phoenissae” 762:—pleonastic, τίνος χάριν ἕνεκ; 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 701d \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; also χάριν τινός <b>as far as regards.., as to</b>.., ἔπους σμικροῦ χ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 443 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; δακρύων χάριν <b>if</b> tears <b>would serve,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “fragment” 557.6; χ. θανάτου πόλιν ἀτείχιστον οἰκοῦμεν 4th-3rd c.BC: Epicurus Philosophus “Gnomologium Vaticanum - Kleine Schriften” 31 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; also, <b>about,</b> ἔπεμφεν ἐπὶ τὴν πενθεράν σου χ. τοῦ κτήματος <b>about</b> the farm, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “PFay.” 126.5 (2nd-3rd c.AD).\">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]—Orig. an <i>accusative</i> in apposition with the sentence, as in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 15.744, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], <b>being a favour, since it is (was) a favour,</b> as is evident in κακῆς γυναικὸς χάριν ἄχαριν ἀπώλετο [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Iphigenia Taurica” 566; τινὸς νίκας ἀκάρπωτον χ. 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 176 (Lyric poetry). \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__VI.2</b></Level3> with Preps.: <br /><Level4><b>__VI.2.a</b></Level4> εἰς χάριν <b>to do a pleasure,</b> οὐδὲν ἐς χ. πράσσων [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “OT” 1353 (Lyric poetry); ἐς χ. τίθεσθαί τι 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Marius” 46; μηδὲ κρίσιν εἰς χ. ἕλκε 1st c.AD(?): Pseudo-Phocylidea 9 (but ἐς τὴν τῶν ξυμμάχων χ.\">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>] in such a way as to earn <b>thanks</b>.. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 3.37); also κατὰ χάριν 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 740c; χάριτος ἕνεκα [prev. work] 771d. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__VI.2.b</b></Level4> πράσσειν τί τινι πρὸς χάριν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 1776 (_anapaest meter_); δρᾶσαι 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Helena” 1281; τοῖσι πολλοῖς πρὸς χάριν λέγειν τι [prev. author] “Hec.” 257, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 4.4.4, “HG” 6.3.7, 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 2.18, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 8.1 (but πρὸς χ. βορᾶς\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] <b>for the sake</b> of it, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 30)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; πρὸς χ., opposed to κλαίων, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “OT” 1152:—but πρὸς χ. εὐσεβίας, just like{χάριν}, 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 8.8; τίνος νόμου ταῦτα πρὸς χ. λέγ; 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 908; πρὸς ἰσχύος χ. 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Medea” 538 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; πρὸς χ. alone, <b>as a favour, freely,</b> πρὸς χ. τε κοὐ βίᾳ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Fragmenta” 28 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; but κορέσαι στόμα πρὸς χ. <b>to</b> their <b>heart's content,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Ph.” 1156 (Lyric poetry). \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__VI.2.c</b></Level4> ἐν χάριτι κρίνειν τινά to decide <b>from partiality</b> to one, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 5.69 \">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]; but also, <b>for</b> one's <b>gratification, pleasure,</b> ἐν χάριτι διδόναι or ποιεῖν τινί τι, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Oeconomicus” 8.10, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedo” 115b: παραλαμβάνειν ἐν χάρισιν \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<b>gratefully,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Lg.” 796b. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__VI.2.d</b></Level4> διὰ χαρίτων εἶναι or γίγνεσθαί [τινι] to be <b>pleasing</b> to one, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Hiero” 9.1, 2. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__VI.2.e</b></Level4> ἐθελοντὶ καὶ μετὰ χάριτος <b>of pure good will,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.BC: Polybius Historicus 2.22.5, etc.; ἐθελούσιοι καὶ χάριτος ἕνεκα ἐξιόντες 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 4.2.11. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__VII</b></Level2> <i>metaphorically</i> of <b>the cypress,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" Gp. 11.4.1 \">Refs</a>]; of some kind of <b>myrtle,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"Scholia 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 17.51 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; of <b>salt,</b> ὅτι τὸ ἀναγκαῖον ἡδὺ ποιοῦσιν (i.e. ἅλες) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.685a. \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level1><b>__B</b></Level1> <b>Χάρις</b>, ἡ, as a mythological <i>proper name</i> declined like{χάρις}, save that the <i>accusative</i> is generally Χάριτα (except [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"“Anthologia Graeca” 5.148 (1st c.BC: Meleager Epigrammaticus), 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “DDeor.” 15.1, 2nd c.AD: Pausanias Periegeta 9.35.4): poetry _dative_ _plural_ Χαρίτεσσι 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 17.51, 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “N.” 9.54; Χάρισσιν [prev. work] 5.54 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]:—<b>Charis,</b> wife of Hephaestus, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 18.382 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; mostly in <i>plural</i> Χάριτες, αἱ, <b>the Graces,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 14.267, 275, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 6.18, 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 2.50, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; three in number, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Theogonia” 907, etc. (τέσσαρες αἱ 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], as a compliment, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Callimachus Epicus “Epigrammata” 52.1)\">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]; attendants of Aphrodite, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 5.338, 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 73, “hymnus ad Venerem” 61, 2nd c.AD: Pausanias Periegeta 6.24.7 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; coupled with Μοῦσαι, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Theogonia” 64 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; κόμαι Χαρίτεσσιν ὁμοῖαι, i.e. like that of the <b>Graces,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 17.51 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; worshipped at Orchomenus in Boeotia, Ἐτεόκλειοι Χάριτες θεαί [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd 